  <static seed="1471" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/SolveLinearEquations/SolveLinearEquationParentheses160.pg">
    <statement><p>Solve the equation.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ {4\mathopen{}\left(p+1\right)-8\mathopen{}\left(p-3\right)}={8}  }</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="31" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\{5\}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
4(p +1) -8(p-3)       \amp = 8 \\
4(p +1) +(-8)(p+(-3)) \amp = 8 \\
4p +4 \cdot 1 +(-8) \cdot p +(-8) \cdot (-3) \amp = 8 \\
4p +4 -8p +24 \amp = 8 \\
4p -8p +4+24 \amp = 8 \\
      -4p +28 \amp = 8 \\
      -4p +28\mathbf{{}-28} \amp = 8\mathbf{{}-28} \\
      -4p             \amp = -20 \\
      \frac{-4p}{-4} \amp = \frac{-20}{-4} \\
      p                      \amp = 5
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>The solution to this equation is <m>5</m>. To stress that this is a value assigned to <m>p</m>, some report <m>p = 5</m>. We can also say that the solution set is <m>\{5\}</m>, or that <m>p\in\left\{5\right\}</m>. If we substitute <m>5</m> in for <m>p</m> in the original equation <m>4\mathopen{}\left(p+1\right)-8\mathopen{}\left(p-3\right)=8</m>, the equation will be true. Please check this on your own; it is an important habit.</p>
</solution>
